erm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

On Wednesday, CBS News editorial and newsgathering chief Adrienne
Roark told staff that she would be leaving the network after just seven mon=
ths in the job. In light of all the myriad controversies and internal drama=
 emanating out of Black Rock in recent months=E2=80=94the Tony Dokoupil=E2=
=80=93Ta-Nehisi Coates dustup, which divided the newsroom; the controversia=
l 60 Minutes segment on Gaza, which invited scrutiny from the Anti-Defamati=
on League; the still-impending settlement with Trump over 60=E2=80=99s Kama=
la
interview; the confounding overhaul ( https://puck.news/cbs-news-very-bad-y=
ear-is-not-getting-better/?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F=
19%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F14%2F25%29&utm_me=
dium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a =
) of Evening News, where ratings continue to slide week by week; Shari=E2=
=80=99s general discontent with all of it; etcetera=E2=80=94Roark=E2=80=99s=
 sudden departure seemed like yet another blemish on the network and, by ex=
tension, its chief executive, Wendy McMahon (even if, admittedly, only
a majority of these things are really her fault).=C2=A0

=C2=A0

McMahon=E2=80=99s decision to give Roark oversight of the newsroom last Aug=
ust, following the departure of Ingrid Cipri=C3=A1n-Matthews, had confused =
many CBS journalists from the outset. A veteran manager of local TV station=
s and onetime CBS stations president, Roark never evidenced the newsroom le=
adership experience historically required of a
major broadcast news chief. (An aside: While visiting the London bureau las=
t year, Roark inadvertently revealed that it was her first time in the coun=
try.) Anyway, McMahon placed her faith in the network=E2=80=99s true editor=
ial lead, Bill Owens, the 60 Minutes executive producer whom McMahon also t=
asked with oversight of Evening News. Of course, that has come with its own=
 problems.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

In any event, Roark wasn=E2=80=99t the right fit. After both sides determin=
ed that she wasn=E2=80=99t up to the challenges of the current moment, she =
got a job at Tegna, the local-TV-stations outfit. (News of her move, which =
the network had hoped to hold until next month, was first reported this wee=
k by Breaker ( https://www.breakermedia.com/?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+Room+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%282%2F19%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2=
F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df=
6c60617da42abd12a ).) No word yet on who will take over the newsroom=E2=80=
=94or whether McMahon still gets to have a
say in who that person might be, or whether it even matters. The parent com=
pany is on the verge of being sold to Skydance, and it=E2=80=99s hard to im=
agine how McMahon fits into the picture.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Indeed, the Paramount-Skydance deal portends substantial changes. Sources c=
lose to the new leadership group at Skydance tell me that McMahon will almo=
st certainly lose her job as head of the news division after the
merger, in part because of their frustration with the aforementioned contro=
versies and management problems. McMahon=E2=80=99s boss, CBS C.E.O. George =
Cheeks, has agreed to stay on at the company, I=E2=80=99m told, and while h=
e has historically been an advocate for her, this is not a fight he cares t=
o wage. And indeed, Cheeks may have his own cause for frustration: I=E2=80=
=99m told that he had asked McMahon ahead of the 60 Minutes Gaza segment wh=
ether she
foresaw any problems with it. She told him that she didn=E2=80=99t, and add=
ed that, if anything, it might be perceived as too sympathetic to Israel. I=
n the end, the segment invited public rebuke from both the ADL and the Amer=
ican Jewish Committee.

=C2=A0

Meanwhile, McMahon may have also irked current and future leadership by str=
ongly advocating against Shari Redstone=E2=80=99s plan to settle the lawsui=
t
that Trump brought against 60 Minutes=E2=80=94an obviously absurd capitulat=
ion that Shari nevertheless sees as a small price to pay for securing appro=
val of the deal. (This may be illogical, on two fronts. One, settling with =
Trump does not necessarily deter future pressure, as Bob Iger and ABC News =
learned the hard way. Two, it=E2=80=99s highly unlikely that Trump will dep=
rive his loyal supporter and donor Larry Ellison and his son David of the a=
sset.)
In any case, McMahon has made her feelings about the settlement known and h=
as worked behind the scenes to make sure other journalists are vocal about =
the dangers of settling, which isn=E2=80=99t exactly being celebrated by he=
r bosses.=C2=A0

On a separate note, the Cheeks re-up is probably the latest confirmation th=
at Jeff Zucker is not headed to CBS, as many persistently wondered back in =
the day, during the quainter age of the
Biden administration. Not only does Zucker have his RedBird IMI fund, of co=
urse, but he=E2=80=99s also a Trump antagonist (an increasingly untrendy po=
sition these days) and, it goes without saying, is almost certainly past th=
e stage of his career where he=E2=80=99ll want to take on a transformation =
job.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Meanwhile, whoever replaces McMahon in the new regime will likely be lookin=
g at a teardown situation=E2=80=94a new evening
news format, possibly a new permanent anchor, a plan for Mornings after Gay=
le King eventually retires, and whatever is necessary to rebuild morale at =
60 after this whole depressing settlement situation passes. It=E2=80=99s a =
tough job, but hopefully the Ellisons pay well.

Burns=E2=80=99s Book
--------------

On Tuesday, a day after I
broke the news ( https://x.com/DylanByers/status/1891682725091852430?utm_ca=
mpaign=3DIn+the+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F19%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+R=
oom+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3D=
customer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), Politico founding editor and p=
atriarch John Harris sent his staff a typically magniloquent memo=E2=80=941=
,400 words, with a 1,100-word addendum, rife with superlatives=E2=80=94anno=
uncing that Alex Burns, his 38-year-old head of news and hand-picked heir a=
pparent, would be ascending still higher up the org chart. As =E2=80=9Cseni=
or executive editor,=E2=80=9D Burns
will lead all North American coverage, including the core Washington report=
, plus the flagship Playbook product, congressional coverage, the New York =
and California verticals, etcetera. His peers, Joe Schatz and Anita Kumar, =
would meanwhile be moved to deputy positions overseeing growth and standard=
s, respectively.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Even for ChatGPT, which capably whittled Harris=E2=80=99s
email down to 180 words, the memo=E2=80=99s significance was clear. Burns=
=E2=80=99s ascension to the penultimate editor job is the culmination of a =
vision Harris has had for years, at least since he first brought Burns back=
 to Politico from the Times in 2022 in an understated associate editor and =
columnist role that belied the real roadmap. Still, there are reasons why B=
urns=E2=80=99s promotion required delicate choreography, Harris=E2=80=99s l=
oquacity notwithstanding.

=C2=A0

While expanding his remit, Burns has ruffled a lot of feathers, as I=E2=80=
=99ve reported on several occasions. As Burns and Harris see it, he=E2=80=
=99s a brilliant journalist trying to elevate standards and provide editori=
al direction in a newsroom that=E2=80=99s lost its edge. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=
=99s very sharp. He doesn=E2=80=99t abide flabby story pitches or shoddy wr=
iting, and Politico has too much of both,=E2=80=9D one Politico insider tol=
d me. But to many in the newsroom, Burns comes across as
pretentious and condescending, with little patience for shortcomings and no=
 regard for diplomacy. The approach, as another insider described it, is, =
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m smarter than you, get with the program, or get the fuc=
k out.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

On some level, Burns=E2=80=99s promotion might seem like a de facto resolut=
ion to that conflict. Harris has now formally made his golden boy the heir =
to his chair. Meanwhile, the owners at Axel and the
rest of the core leadership team seem to have faith and conviction in Burns=
=E2=80=94including C.E.O. Goli Sheikholeslami, and executive vice president=
 Jonathan Greenberger, a former ABC News executive producer who may himself=
 ascend to the C.E.O. role, in tandem with Burns=E2=80=99s rise to the top =
editorial role in a few years time. And for whatever it=E2=80=99s worth, ma=
ny of the most vocal Burns shit-talkers have already been shown the door or=
, in some cases, left of their own
volition. =E2=80=9CBurns irks a lot of folks in the newsroom but IMO he is =
the right pick,=E2=80=9D emailed one insider, perhaps best summarizing the =
situation.

=C2=A0

In his own memo to staff on Tuesday, titled =E2=80=9Cthe best version of Po=
litico,=E2=80=9D Burns promised a faster editorial process, a more unified =
newsroom, and stronger promotion, among other things. (One gripe against Bu=
rns is that his exacting standards slowed down the
editorial process; in fairness, that probably had more to do with the convo=
luted structure Harris is now trying to rectify.) But the guy also has a to=
n of work ahead of him outside of operational process work and kumbaya shit=
=2E=C2=A0

=C2=A0

As I=E2=80=99ve written before, Politico=E2=80=99s core Washington coverage=
 feels extremely inert right now. The decision to give the flagship Playboo=
k enterprise to Jack
Blanchard, a Brit who ran Politico=E2=80=99s U.K. operation and is only now=
 learning Washington=E2=80=99s inner workings=E2=80=94and, it seems, Americ=
an politics=E2=80=94has already yielded some embarrassing results ( https:/=
/x.com/jacobrubashkin/status/1891859473527914912?s=3D46&utm_campaign=3DIn+t=
he+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F19%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F14%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ). The long-dormant congressional coverage, wh=
ile finally showing signs of life, still lives in the shadow of Jake Sherma=
n and Anna Palmer=E2=80=99s Punchbowl.
At the White House, Politico is notably short on reporters with real ties t=
o Trump and his inner circle. Meanwhile, if the decision to place former NB=
C News correspondent Dasha Burns in charge of that bureau is indicative of =
some strategy, we still have yet to see what it is. (Maybe Harris has some =
other long-gestating master plan to be revealed in a verbose memo in a few =
months=E2=80=99 time.)

=C2=A0

Anyway,
these are critiques Harris and Burns have heard before=E2=80=94and ones tha=
t, in their view, not only misunderstand the long-term strategy underway, b=
ut also downplay Politico=E2=80=99s strengths, from its defense coverage, t=
o those California and New York verticals, to its highly lucrative Politico=
 Pro vertical, which is withstanding DOGE penny-pinching. But that, too, ma=
y be indicative of the fundamental problem: In the same way Harris and Burn=
s don=E2=80=99t want to suffer the complaints of their newsroom, they also
don=E2=80=99t seem to want to reckon with how the core product=E2=80=94the =
one around which so much of their business revolves=E2=80=94is being receiv=
ed in the market. To hear Harris tell it, Jack Blanchard is the second comi=
ng of Jonathan Swan, and Dasha Burns the next Maggie Haberman. Eavesdrop on=
 any conversation on Capitol Hill or at the White House, and it becomes qui=
te clear that they=E2=80=99re reading the wrong weather vane. But maybe the=
y=E2=80=99re just smarter than we are.

