major broadcast news chief. (An aside: While visiting the London bureau las=
t year, Roark inadvertently revealed that it was her first time in the coun=
try.) Anyway, McMahon placed her faith in the network=E2=80=99s <em>true </=
em>editorial lead, <strong>Bill Owens</strong>, the <em>60 Minutes </em>exe=
cutive producer whom McMahon also tasked with oversight of <em>Evening News=
</em>. Of course, that has come with its own problems.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">In any event, Roark wasn=E2=80=99t the right fit. After=
 both sides determined that she wasn=E2=80=99t up to the challenges of the =
current moment, she got a job at Tegna, the local-TV-stations outfit. (News=
 of her move, which the network had hoped to hold until next month, was fir=
st reported this week by <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9=
pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWSVdoMHd1eXlxZl9DUkRuVUU2Zz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnJlYWtlcm1lZGlhLmNvbS8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPUluK3RoZStSb29tKy0rU=
1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MiUyRjE5JTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1JbitUaGUrUm9v=
bSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODIlMkYxNCUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9=
hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MT=
dkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoyM=
DkxMTg5fQ/5dbabf76a7358150a5c51be44a806d68d7284aa3d79925c77c6d593414e9ee84"=
 style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">Breaker</a>.) No word y=
et on who will take over the newsroom=E2=80=94or whether McMahon still gets=
 to have a
say in who that person might be, or whether it even matters. The parent com=
pany is on the verge of being sold to Skydance, and it=E2=80=99s hard to im=
agine how McMahon fits into the picture.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;marg=
in-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Indeed, =
the Paramount-Skydance deal portends substantial changes. Sources close to =
the new leadership group at Skydance tell me that McMahon will almost certa=
inly lose her job as head of the news division after the
merger, in part because of their frustration with the aforementioned contro=
versies and management problems. McMahon=E2=80=99s boss, CBS C.E.O. <strong=
>George Cheeks</strong>, <em>has</em> agreed to stay on at the company, I=
=E2=80=99m told, and while he has historically been an advocate for her, th=
is is not a fight he cares to wage. And indeed, Cheeks may have his own cau=
se for frustration: I=E2=80=99m told that he had asked McMahon <em>ahead </=
em>of the <em>60 Minutes</em> Gaza segment whether she
foresaw any problems with it. She told him that she didn=E2=80=99t, and add=
ed that, if anything, it might be perceived as <em>too</em> sympathetic to =
Israel. In the end, the segment invited public rebuke from both the ADL and=
 the American Jewish Committee.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"=
>=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Meanwhile, McMahon may =
have also irked current and future leadership by strongly advocating <em>ag=
ainst </em>Shari Redstone=E2=80=99s plan to settle the lawsuit
that Trump brought against <em>60 Minutes</em>=E2=80=94an obviously absurd =
capitulation that Shari nevertheless sees as a small price to pay for secur=
ing approval of the deal. (This may be illogical, on two fronts. One, settl=
ing with Trump does not necessarily deter future pressure, as <strong>Bob I=
ger </strong>and ABC News learned the hard way. Two, it=E2=80=99s highly un=
likely that Trump will deprive his loyal supporter and donor <strong>Larry =
Ellison</strong> and his son <strong>David</strong> of the asset.)
In any case, McMahon has made her feelings about the settlement known and h=
as worked behind the scenes to make sure other journalists are vocal about =
the dangers of settling, which isn=E2=80=99t exactly being celebrated by he=
r bosses.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><br/>On a separ=
ate note, the Cheeks re-up is probably the latest confirmation that <strong=
>Jeff Zucker </strong>is <em>not </em>headed to CBS, as many persistently w=
ondered back in the day, during the quainter age of the
<strong>Biden </strong>administration. Not only does Zucker have his RedBir=
d IMI fund, of course, but he=E2=80=99s also a Trump antagonist (an increas=
ingly untrendy position these days) and, it goes without saying, is almost =
certainly past the stage of his career where he=E2=80=99ll want to take on =
a transformation job.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Meanwhile, whoever replaces McMahon in the ne=
w regime will likely be looking at a teardown situation=E2=80=94a new eveni=
ng
news format, possibly a new permanent anchor, a plan for <em>Mornings </em>=
after <strong>Gayle King </strong>eventually retires, and whatever is neces=
sary to rebuild morale at <em>60 </em>after this whole depressing settlemen=
t situation passes. It=E2=80=99s a tough job, but hopefully the Ellisons pa=
y well.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
