reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"=
><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">On Tuesday, a day after I
<a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktx=
clJLZ0dWSVdoMHd1eXlxZl9DUkRuVUU2Zz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly94LmNvbS9EeWxhbkJ=
5ZXJzL3N0YXR1cy8xODkxNjgyNzI1MDkxODUyNDMwP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1Jbit0aGUrUm9vbS=
stK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODIlMkYxOSUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9SW4rVGhlK=
1Jvb20rLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgyJTJGMTQlMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1h=
aWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzY=
wNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZC=
I6MjA5MTE5MH0/9994f23204b391e028b85ab13ebaa3ff7ea5079f9ede65dff73a8fc68656f=
777" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">broke the news</a>,=
 Politico founding editor and patriarch <strong>John Harris </strong>sent h=
is staff a typically magniloquent memo=E2=80=941,400 words, with a 1,100-wo=
rd addendum, rife with superlatives=E2=80=94announcing that <strong>Alex Bu=
rns</strong>, his 38-year-old head of news and hand-picked heir apparent, w=
ould be ascending still higher up the org chart. As =E2=80=9Csenior executi=
ve editor,=E2=80=9D Burns
will lead all North American coverage, including the core Washington report=
, plus the flagship Playbook product, congressional coverage, the New York =
and California verticals, etcetera. His peers, <strong>Joe Schatz</strong> =
and <strong>Anita Kumar</strong>, would meanwhile be moved to deputy positi=
ons overseeing growth and standards, respectively.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;=
">Even for ChatGPT, which capably whittled Harris=E2=80=99s
email down to 180 words, the memo=E2=80=99s significance was clear. Burns=
=E2=80=99s ascension to the penultimate editor job is the culmination of a =
vision Harris has had for years, at least since he first brought Burns back=
 to Politico from the <em>Times</em> in 2022 in an understated associate ed=
itor and columnist role that belied the real roadmap. Still, there are reas=
ons why Burns=E2=80=99s promotion required delicate choreography, Harris=E2=
=80=99s loquacity notwithstanding.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">While expanding his remit, Burns h=
as ruffled <em>a lot</em> of feathers, as I=E2=80=99ve reported on several =
occasions. As Burns and Harris see it, he=E2=80=99s a brilliant journalist =
trying to elevate standards and provide editorial direction in a newsroom t=
hat=E2=80=99s lost its edge. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s very sharp. He doesn=E2=
=80=99t abide flabby story pitches or shoddy writing, and Politico has too =
much of both,=E2=80=9D one Politico insider told me. But to many in the new=
sroom, Burns comes across as
pretentious and condescending, with little patience for shortcomings and no=
 regard for diplomacy. The approach, as another insider described it, is, =
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m smarter than you, get with the program, or get the fuc=
k out.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">On some level, Burns=E2=80=99s promotio=
n might seem like a de facto resolution to that conflict. Harris has now fo=
rmally made his golden boy the heir to his chair. Meanwhile, the owners at =
Axel and the
rest of the core leadership team seem to have faith and conviction in Burns=
=E2=80=94including C.E.O. <strong>Goli Sheikholeslami</strong>, and executi=
ve vice president <strong>Jonathan Greenberger</strong>, a former ABC News =
executive producer who may himself ascend to the C.E.O. role, in tandem wit=
h Burns=E2=80=99s rise to the top editorial role in a few years time. And f=
or whatever it=E2=80=99s worth, many of the most vocal Burns shit-talkers h=
ave already been shown the door or, in some cases, left of their own
volition. =E2=80=9CBurns irks a lot of folks in the newsroom but IMO he is =
the right pick,=E2=80=9D emailed one insider, perhaps best summarizing the =
situation.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In his own memo to staff on Tuesday, title=
d =E2=80=9Cthe best version of Politico,=E2=80=9D Burns promised a faster e=
ditorial process, a more unified newsroom, and stronger promotion, among ot=
her things. (One gripe against Burns is that his exacting standards slowed =
down the
editorial process; in fairness, that probably had more to do with the convo=
luted structure Harris is now trying to rectify.) But the guy also has a to=
n of work ahead of him outside of operational process work and kumbaya shit=
=2E=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">As I=E2=80=99ve written before, Politico=E2=80=
=99s core Washington coverage feels extremely inert right now. The decision=
 to give the flagship Playbook enterprise to <strong>Jack
Blanchard</strong>, a Brit who ran Politico=E2=80=99s U.K. operation and is=
 only now learning Washington=E2=80=99s inner workings=E2=80=94and, it seem=
s, American politics=E2=80=94has already yielded some <a href=3D"https://em=
ail.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWSVdoMHd1eXlxZ=
l9DUkRuVUU2Zz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly94LmNvbS9qYWNvYnJ1YmFzaGtpbi9zdGF0dXMv=
MTg5MTg1OTQ3MzUyNzkxNDkxMj9zPTQ2XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPUluK3RoZStSb29tKy0=
rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MiUyRjE5JTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1JbitUaGUrUm=
9vbSstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODIlMkYxNCUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpb=
F9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2=
MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo=
yMDkxMTkxfQ/74faf56e5552ca12f74935f98b891d915206b03855575273d09741447be7e8d=
4" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">embarrassing results<=
/a>. The long-dormant congressional coverage, while finally showing signs o=
f life, still lives in the shadow of <strong>Jake Sherman </strong>and <str=
ong>Anna Palmer</strong>=E2=80=99s Punchbowl.
At the White House, Politico is notably short on reporters with real ties t=
o <strong>Trump</strong> and his inner circle. Meanwhile, if the decision t=
o place former NBC News correspondent <strong>Dasha Burns </strong>in charg=
e of that bureau is indicative of some strategy, we still have yet to see w=
hat it is. (Maybe Harris has some other long-gestating master plan to be re=
vealed in a verbose memo in a few months=E2=80=99 time.)</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Anyway,
these are critiques Harris and Burns have heard before=E2=80=94and ones tha=
t, in their view, not only misunderstand the long-term strategy underway, b=
ut also downplay Politico=E2=80=99s strengths, from its defense coverage, t=
o those California and New York verticals, to its highly lucrative Politico=
 Pro vertical, which is withstanding DOGE penny-pinching. But that, too, ma=
y be indicative of the fundamental problem: In the same way Harris and Burn=
s don=E2=80=99t want to suffer the complaints of their newsroom, they also
don=E2=80=99t seem to want to reckon with how the core product=E2=80=94the =
one around which so much of their business revolves=E2=80=94is being receiv=
ed in the market. To hear Harris tell it, Jack Blanchard is the second comi=
ng of <strong>Jonathan Swan</strong>, and Dasha Burns the next <strong>Magg=
ie Haberman</strong>. Eavesdrop on any conversation on Capitol Hill or at t=
he White House, and it becomes quite clear that they=E2=80=99re reading the=
 wrong weather vane. But maybe they=E2=80=99re just smarter than we are.</p=
></div>
